The '''Cisco Certified Entry Networking Technician''' (CCENT)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/training-events/training-certifications/certifications/entry/ccent.html|title=CCENT|website=Cisco}}</ref> certification is the first stage of [[Cisco certifications|Cisco's certification]] system.  The CCENT certification is an interim step to Associate level or directly with [[CCNA]] and [[Cisco certifications#CCDA|CCDA]] [[Professional certification (computer technology)|certifications]]. While the CCENT covers basic networking knowledge; it does not get involved with the more intricate technical aspects of the Cisco [[routing]] and switching and [[network design]]. The certification does validate the skills essential for entry-level network support positions. CCENT qualified individuals have the knowledge and skill to install, manage, maintain and troubleshoot a small enterprise branch network, including [[network security]]. The CCENT curriculum covers networking fundamentals, WAN technologies, basic security, routing and switching fundamentals, and configuring simple networks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cisco.com/web/learning/le3/le2/le45/learning_certification_level_home.html |title=CCENT Certification |author=Cisco|accessdate=May 3, 2011}}</ref> The applicable training is Cisco ICND1 ("Interconnecting Cisco Network Devices, Part 1") and the exam is ("100-105" ICND1), and it costs $165 retail.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cisco.com/web/learning/le3/le2/le45/learning_certification_level_home.html |title=CCENT - Career Certifications & Paths - Cisco Systems}}</ref> The certification is valid for 3 years, and professionals may retake the exam to re-certify.

