{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}} {{Use British English|date=October 2017}} [[File:Portrait of James Donaldson.jpg|right|thumb|Sir James Donaldson, LLD.]] [[File:The grave of Chancellor James Donaldson, St Andrews Cathedral churchyard.JPG|thumb|The grave of Chancellor James Donaldson and his family, St Andrews Cathedral churchyard]] '''Sir James Donaldson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSE}} (26 April 1831, [[Aberdeen]] – 1915), was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[classical scholar]], and educational and theological writer.
==Life== He was born in [[Aberdeen]] on 26 April 1831.
He was educated at [[Aberdeen Grammar School]], [[Marischal College]], [[Aberdeen]], [[New College, London|New College]], [[London]], and [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin University]]. In 1854 he was appointed [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|Rector]] of the [[Stirling High School]] where he remained for two years, before leaving for the [[Royal High School of Edinburgh]], of which he was appointed Rector in 1866.
He was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1867, his proposer being [[Alexander Keith Johnston (1804-1871)|Alexander Keith Johnston]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783–2002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0 902 198 84 X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp1.pdf}}</ref>
He became in 1881 Professor of [[Humanities|Humanity]] in the [[University of Aberdeen]], and in 1890 [[University principal|Principal]] of the [[University of St Andrews]] by the Universities (Scotland) Act.
He was [[knight]]ed by [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]] in 1907, and was awarded an [[Doctor of Laws|LL.D.]] by the [[University of Glasgow]] and an [[Honorary degree|honorary]] [[Doctor of Divinity]] by the [[University of Aberdeen]] in recognition of his work in Church history.
He died on 9 March 1915.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783–2002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0 902 198 84 X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp1.pdf}}</ref> and is buried with his wife in the churchyard of [[St Andrews Cathedral]]. He also has a memorial in the [[Church of St John the Evangelist, Edinburgh]]. He was succeeded in his role as Principal by [[Alexander Stewart (moderator)|Very Rev Prof Alexander Stewart]], but Stewart died only a few months later.<ref>Aberdeen Press and Journal 23 July 1915</ref>
==Principal works== *''A Modern [[Greek language|Greek]] [[Grammar]] for the Use of Classical Students'' (1853) *''Lyra Graeca'' (1854), specimens of Greek [[lyric poetry]] from [[Callinus]] to [[Alexandros Soutsos]] *''The Ante-Nicene Christian Library'', in collaboration with [[Alexander Roberts]] (24 vols., 1867–72) *''A Critical History of [[Christian]] Literature and Christian [[Doctrine]] from the Death of the Apostles to the [[First Council of Nicaea|Nicene Council]]'' (i.-iii., 1864-1866; new ed. of i. as ''The Apostolical Fathers'', 1874) *''Lectures on the [[History of Education]] in [[Prussia]] and [[England]]'' (1874) *''Expiatory and Substitutory Sacrifices of the Greeks'' (1875) *''The [[Westminster Confession of Faith]] and the [[Thirty-Nine Articles]] of the [[Church of England]]'' (1905) *''Woman, her position and influence in ancient Greece and Rome'' (1907)<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of ''Woman: her position and influence in ancient Greece and Rome'' by James Donaldson|journal=[[Athenaeum (British magazine)|The Athenaeum]]|date=2 March 1907|issue=4140|pages=248–249|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wt9BAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA248}}</ref>
