{{Infobox scientist | name = Jean-Louis Calandrini | image = Jean-Louis Calandrini.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = Jean-Louis Calandrini (1703-1758). Portrait by the Geneva painter [[Robert Gardelle]] in 1760. | birth_date = August 30, 1703 | birth_place = [[Geneva]], [[Republic and Canton of Geneva#History|Republic of Geneva]] | death_date = December 29, 1758 | death_place = [[Geneva]], [[Republic and Canton of Geneva#History|Republic of Geneva]] | residence = [[Geneva]] | nationality = [[Republic and Canton of Geneva#History|Genevan]] | field = [[Mathematics]], [[philosophy]], and [[physics]] | work_institutions = [[Academy of Geneva]] | alma_mater = [[Academy of Geneva]] | doctoral_advisor = <!--pls insert--> | doctoral_students = <!--pls insert--> | known_for = | prizes = | religion = | footnotes = }}
'''Jean-Louis Calandrini''' (August 30, 1703 – December 29, 1758) was a Genevan scientist. He was a professor of [[mathematics]] and [[philosophy]]. He was the author of some studies on the [[Aurora (astronomy)|aurora borealis]], [[comets]], and the effects of [[lightning]], as well as of an important but unpublished work on flat and spherical [[trigonometry]]. He also wrote a commentary on the ''[[Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica|Principia]]'' of [[Isaac Newton]] (published in [[Geneva]], 1739–42), for which he wrote approximately one hundred [[footnotes]].
He was also known as a botanist. The genus ''[[Calandrinia]]'' was named after him.<ref name="Quattrocchi1999">{{cite book|first=Umberto|last= Quattrocchi|title=CRC World Dictionary of Plant Names: Common Names, Scientific Names, Eponyms, Synonyms, and Etymology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A68qyOyhOdkC&pg=PA392|date=1999|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-2673-8|page=392}}</ref>
His father was a pastor, also named Jean-Louis, and his mother was Michée Du Pan. He wass the grandnephew of [[Bénédict Calandrini]] ([[:de:Bénédict Calandrini|de]]) ([[:fr:Bénédict Calandrini|fr]]). In 1729, he married Renée Lullin. At the Academy of Geneva, he obtained his thesis in physics (1722). In 1724, Calandrini was named mathematics professor at the same time as [[Gabriel Cramer]], but he first undertook a three-year journey to France and England. He was appointed professor of philosophy from 1734 to 1750. He also played an active role on the political scene of Geneva.
