[[File:Millicent Kittredge Blake.png|thumb|Millicent Kittredge Blake]]
'''Millicent Kittredge Blake''' (alternate spelling, Meliscent; née Millicent Kittredge; January 11, 1822 - November 27, 1907) was an [[Oakland, California]] pioneer, and an American educator from the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]]. She founded the [[Oakland Female Seminary]] (aka Oakland Seminary for Young Ladies; Blake Seminary) on November 8, 1858.{{sfn|University of the Pacific|1976|p=163}} It was the first girls school established to the west of the [[Mississippi River]]. 

Her birthplace was [[Essex, New York]], upon historic [[Lake Champlain]]. She is a descendant on the maternal side, of [[Cotton Mather]], and of those physicians who bear the name of Kittredge.{{sfn|Californian Publishing Company|1892|p=9}} She married [[George Mansfield Blake]], [[List of mayors of Oakland, California|mayor of Oakland]], and business partner of her brother, [[Francis Kittredge Shattuck]].{{sfn|Anderson|2015|p=40}}{{sfn|Comstock|2013|p=32}}

She studied and became a teacher. After a successful management of private schools in her native State, she came to Oakland in 1852, and as soon as its growth warranted the venture, her seminary for young ladies was opened. Although discouraged by friends, who considered success impossible in so new a country, Blake kept steadily on, and eventually succeeded in establishing her school.{{sfn|Californian Publishing Company|1892|p=9}} For half a century, Blake was a paramount factor in the educational work of this county. Not only in her work of founding and maintaining the seminary, but also in the work of founding and upbuilding the [[University of California]], and other western institutions of education.{{sfn|Bronson|Hunt|1907|p=44}}

